PRINCETON, NJ. The son
of a slain African political lead
err has appealed for an official
inquiry to determine who killed
his father and why.


He is Fernando E. Olympic,
a 23-year-old Princeton junior,
son of President Sylvanus Olym-
pto of Togo, who was shot and
killed in a military coup d. etat
in Lone. Togo's capital, on Jan.
Is, 1868.


In a letter to The New York
Times dated on the first ami
versary of his father death the
younger Olympic recalled that
the crime had gone unpublished.

An investigation indicated the

Herbert Neal, formerly direc-
tor of marketing research for
Chock Full ONuts, has been ap-
pointed to the Household Products
Division of Lever Brothers Com
pany as an assistant roduct man
ager, according to an announce
ment by c. E. Palmer, a mer-
chandising manager for the d.
vision, which markets the COM
pany's soaps, detergents and
other household products.


Neal joined Lever Brothers
last October, and had been tenn
porarily assigned to the field
sales force. Before serving two
years with Chock Full o. Nuts,
he had been associated with two
New York advertising agencies
Young & Rubicam and Batten,
Barton, Durstine & Osborne--in
various marketing research ca
pacities.


A graduate of both Harvard
College and the Harvard Grad
uate Business School with an
ALB. degree in economics and an
M.B.A. in business administra-
tion, he lectured on marketing for
two years at Rutgers Universitys
Graduate School of Business.


Mr.. Neal served with the US.
Army during World War II, seeing
action in India and Burma. He
resides with his wife and two
children in New Jersey, where he
is a member of the Pequannock
Township School Board.
